# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chalk-terminal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ANSI sequences were introduced in the 1970s to replace vendor-specific sequences and became widespread in the computer equipment market by the early 1980s.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Although hardware text terminals have become increasingly rare in the 21st century, the relevance of the ANSI standard persists because a great majority of terminal emulators and command consoles interpret at least a portion of the ANSI standard.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Almost all manufacturers of video terminals added vendor-specific escape sequences to perform operations such as placing the cursor at arbitrary positions on the screen.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Hazeltine 1500 had a similar feature, invoked using `~`, `DC1` and then the X and Y positions separated with a comma.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] While the two terminals had identical functionality in this regard, different control sequences had to be used to invoke them.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As these sequences were different for different terminals, elaborate libraries such as termcap ("terminal capabilities") and utilities such as tput had to be created so programs could use the same API to work with any terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In addition, many of these terminals required sending numbers (such as row and column) as the binary values of the characters; for some programming languages, and for systems that did not use ASCII internally, it was often difficult to turn a number into the correct character.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI standard attempted to address these problems by making a command set that all terminals would use and requiring all numeric information to be transmitted as ASCII numbers.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The first standard in the series was **ECMA-48**, adopted in 1976.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It was a continuation of a series of character coding standards, the first one being ECMA-6 from 1965, a 7-bit standard from which ISO 646 originates.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The name "ANSI escape sequence" dates from 1979 when ANSI adopted ANSI X3.64.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI X3L2 committee collaborated with the ECMA committee TC 1 to produce nearly identical standards.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These two standards were merged into an international standard, ISO 6429.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 1994, ANSI withdrew its standard in favor of the international standard.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The first popular video terminal to support these sequences was the Digital VT100, introduced in 1978.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This model was very successful in the market, which sparked a variety of VT100 clones, among the earliest and most popular of which was the much more affordable Zenith Z-19 in 1979.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Others included the Qume QVT-108, Televideo TVI-970, Wyse WY-99GT as well as optional "VT100" or "VT103" or "ANSI" modes with varying degrees of compatibility on many other brands.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The popularity of these gradually led to more and more software (especially bulletin board systems and other online services) assuming the escape sequences worked, leading to almost all new terminals and emulator programs supporting them.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 1981, ANSI X3.64 was adopted for use in the US government by FIPS publication 86.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Later, the US government stopped duplicating industry standards, so FIPS pub.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ECMA-48 has been updated several times and is currently at its 5th edition, from 1991.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It is also adopted by ISO and IEC as standard **ISO/IEC 6429**.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A version is adopted as a Japanese Industrial Standard, as JIS X 0211.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Related standards include ITU T.61, the Teletex standard, and the **ISO/IEC 8613**, the Open Document Architecture standard (mainly ISO/IEC 8613-6 or ITU T.416).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The two systems share many escape codes with the ANSI system, with extensions that are not necessarily meaningful to computer terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Both systems quickly fell into disuse, but ECMA-48 does mark the extensions used in them as reserved.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In the early 1980s, large amounts of software directly used these sequences to update screen displays.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This included everything on VMS (which assumed DEC terminals), most software designed to be portable on CP/M home computers, and significant amounts of Unix software, as it was easier to use than the termcap libraries.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators for communicating with remote machines almost always implement ANSI escape codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This includes anything written to communicate with bulletin-board systems on home and personal computers.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] On Unix terminal emulators such as xterm also can communicate with software running on the same machine, and thus software running in X11 under a terminal emulator could assume the ability to write these sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As computers got more powerful even built-in displays started supporting them, allowing software to be portable between CP/M systems.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There were attempts to extend the escape sequences to support printers and as an early PDF-like document storage format, the Open Document Architecture.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The IBM PC, introduced in 1981, did not support these or any other escape sequences for updating the screen.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Only a few control characters (BEL, CR, LF, BS) were interpreted by the underlying BIOS.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Any display effects had to be done with BIOS calls, which were notoriously slow, or by directly manipulating the IBM PC hardware.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This made any interesting software non-portable and led to the need to duplicate details of the display hardware in PC Clones.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] DOS version 2.0 included an optional device driver named ANSI.SYS.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Poor performance, and the fact that it was not installed by default, meant software rarely (if ever) took advantage of it.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Windows Console did not support ANSI escape sequences, nor did Microsoft provide any method to enable them.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some replacements such as JP Software's TCC (formerly 4NT), Michael J.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Mefford's ANSI.COM, Jason Hood's ANSICON and Maximus5's ConEmu enabled ANSI escape sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Software such as the Python colorama package or Cygwin modified text in-process as it was sent to the console, extracting the ANSI Escape sequences and emulating them with Windows calls.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 2016, Microsoft released the Windows 10 version 1511 update which unexpectedly implemented support for ANSI escape sequences, over three decades after the debut of Windows.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This was done alongside Windows Subsystem for Linux, apparently to allow Unix-like terminal-based software to use the Windows Console.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Windows PowerShell 5.1 enabled this by default, and PowerShell 6 made it possible to embed the necessary ESC character into a string with `e.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Windows Terminal, introduced in 2019, supports the sequences by default.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Since Windows 11 22H2 and Windows Terminal 1.15, Windows Terminal replaces Windows Console as the default.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Almost all users assume some functions of some single-byte characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The general format for an ANSI-compliant escape sequence is defined by ANSI X3.41 (equivalent to ECMA-35 or ISO/IEC 2022).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The escape sequences consist only of bytes in the range 0x20—0x7F (all the non-control ASCII characters), and can be parsed without looking ahead.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The behavior when a control character, a byte with the high bit set, or a byte that is not part of any valid sequence is encountered before the end is undefined.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x40 to 0x5F, the escape sequence is of type `Fe`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Its interpretation is delegated to the applicable C1 control code standard.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Accordingly, all escape sequences corresponding to C1 control codes from ANSI X3.64 / ECMA-48 follow this format.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The standard says that, in 8-bit environments, the control functions corresponding to type `Fe` escape sequences (those from the set of C1 control codes) can be represented as single bytes in the 0x80–0x9F range.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This is possible in character encodings conforming to the provisions for an 8-bit code made in ISO 2022, such as the ISO 8859 series.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, in character encodings used on modern devices such as UTF-8 or CP-1252, those codes are often used for other purposes, so only the 2-byte sequence is typically used.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In the case of UTF-8, representing a C1 control code via the C1 Controls and Latin-1 Supplement block results in a different two-byte code (e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] 0xC2,0x8E for U+008E), but no space is saved this way.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] All common sequences just use the parameters as a series of semicolon-separated numbers such as `1;2;3`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Missing numbers are treated as `0` (`1;;3` acts like the middle number is `0`, and no parameters at all in `ESC[m` acts like a `0` reset code).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some sequences (such as CUU) treat `0` as `1` in order to make missing parameters useful.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A subset of arrangements was declared "private" so that terminal manufacturers could insert their own sequences without conflicting with the standard.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Sequences containing the parameter bytes `<=>?` or the final bytes 0x70–0x7E (`p–z{|}~`) are private.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The behavior of the terminal is undefined in the case where a CSI sequence contains any character outside of the range 0x20–0x7E.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These illegal characters are either C0 control characters (the range 0–0x1F), DEL (0x7F), or bytes with the high bit set.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Possible responses are to ignore the byte, to process it immediately, and furthermore whether to continue with the CSI sequence, to abort it immediately, or to ignore the rest of it.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The control sequence `CSI *n* m`, named Select Graphic Rendition (SGR), sets display attributes.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Several attributes can be set in the same sequence, separated by semicolons.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Each display attribute remains in effect until a following occurrence of SGR resets it.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If no codes are given, `CSI m` is treated as `CSI 0 m` (reset / normal).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The original specification only had 8 colors, and just gave them names.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The SGR parameters 30–37 selected the foreground color, while 40–47 selected the background.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Quite a few terminals implemented "bold" (SGR code 1) as a brighter color rather than a different font, thus providing 8 additional foreground colors.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Usually you could not get these as background colors, though sometimes inverse video (SGR code 7) would allow that.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Examples: to get black letters on white background use `ESC[30;47m`, to get red use `ESC[31m`, to get bright red use `ESC[1;31m`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] To reset colors to their defaults, use `ESC[39;49m` (not supported on some terminals), or reset all attributes with `ESC[0m`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Later terminals added the ability to directly specify the "bright" colors with 90–97 and 100–107.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The chart below shows a few examples of how classical standards and modern terminal emulators translate the 4-bit color codes into 24-bit color codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The colors displayed by these values vary across terminal/emulator implementations as the recognized ECMA-48 and ITU's T.416 specifications do not define a specific color palette for this lookup table.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] While it is common to use the above formula for the color palette, in particular the algorithm and choice of colors for the 16-231 cube values differs between implementations.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The color palette and algorithm used by XTerm is specified below as a sample.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There has also been a similar but incompatible 88-color encoding using the same escape sequence, seen in `rxvt` and `xterm-88color`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As "true color" graphic cards with 16 to 24 bits of color became common, applications began to support 24-bit colors.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators supporting setting 24-bit foreground and background colors with escape sequences include Xterm, KDE's Konsole, and iTerm, as well as all libvte based terminals, including GNOME Terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This syntax, initially implemented in XTerm, is based on a reading of the ISO/IEC 8613-6 specification, specifically that SGR 38 / SGR 48 followed by the parameter "2" can specify a "direct color" in RGB space..
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As the first widely-used implementation, this specification of RGB values using semicolon separators is widely supported by terminal emulators that include 24-bit color support.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As with the 8-bit color codes, there is a very similar specification of 24-bit color in the ITU's T.416 Open Document Architecture (ODA) and interchange format: Character content architectures, which was adopted as ISO/IEC 8613-6 but ended up as a commercial failure.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] where `Color-Space` indicates the Color-Space associated with the given tolerance: `0` for CIELUV or `1` for CIELAB.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The semicolon-based RGB specification is the most widely supported, but both it and the RGB variant of ITU T.416 are supported by many terminal emulators.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This system, although poorly documented, became widespread enough for Fedora and RHEL to consider using it as a simpler and more universal detection mechanism compared to querying the now-updated libraries.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some terminal emulators (urxvt, Konsole) set `$COLORFGBG` to report the color scheme of the terminal (mainly light vs. dark background).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This behavior originated in S-Lang and is used by vim.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Gnome-terminal refuses to add this behavior, as the syntax for the value is not agreed upon, the value cannot be changed upon a runtime change of the palette, and more "proper" xterm OSC 4/10/11 sequences already exist.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It has become conventional to use the `NO_COLOR` environment variable to disable colors unconditionally.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Most Operating System Command sequences were defined by Xterm, but many are also supported by other terminal emulators.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For historical reasons, Xterm can end the command with `BEL` (0x07) as well as the standard `ST` (0x9C or 0x1B 0x5C).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, Xterm allows the icon name and window title to be set by `ESC ]0;this is the title BEL`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A non-xterm extension is the hyperlink, `ESC ]8;;link ST` from 2017, used by VTE, iTerm2, and mintty, among others.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Linux console uses `ESC ] P n rr gg bb` to change the palette, which, if hard-coded into an application, may hang other terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, appending `ST` will be ignored by Linux and form a proper, ignorable sequence for other terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x60—0x7E, the escape sequence is of type `Fs`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This type is used for control functions individually registered with the ISO-IR registry.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A table of these is listed under ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x30—0x3F, the escape sequence is of type `Fp`, which is set apart for up to sixteen private-use control functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x20—0x2F, the escape sequence is of type `nF`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Said byte is followed by any number of additional bytes in this range, and then a byte in the range 0x30-0x7E.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These escape sequences are further subcategorised by the low two bits of the first byte, e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] "type `2F`" for sequences where the first byte is 0x22; and by whether the final byte is in the range 0x30—0x3F indicating private use (e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Most of the `nFt` sequences are for changing the current character set, and are listed in ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the first byte is '#' the public sequences are reserved for additional ISO-IR registered individual control functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] No such sequences are presently registered.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Type `3Fp` sequences (which includes ones starting with '#') are available for private-use control functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 2 J` — This clears the screen and, on some devices, locates the cursor to the y,x position 1,1 (upper left corner).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The green may be a dark, dull green, so you may wish to enable Bold with the sequence `CSI 1 m` which would make it bright green, or combined as `CSI 32 ; 1 m`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some implementations use the Bold state to make the character Bright.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 0 ; 6 8 ; "DIR" ; 13 p` — This reassigns the key F10 to send to the keyboard buffer the string "DIR" and ENTER, which in the DOS command line would display the contents of the current directory.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] (MS-DOS ANSI.SYS only) This was sometimes used for ANSI bombs.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This is a private-use code (as indicated by the letter p), using a non-standard extension to include a string-valued parameter.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Following the letter of the standard would consider the sequence to end at the letter D.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI s` — This saves the cursor position.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Using the sequence `CSI u` will restore it to the position.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Say the current cursor position is 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The sequence `CSI s` will save those two numbers.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Now you can move to a different cursor position, such as 20(y) and 3(x), using the sequence `CSI 20 ; 3 H` or `CSI 20 ; 3 f`.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Now if you use the sequence CSI u the cursor position will return to 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some terminals require the DEC sequences `ESC 7` / `ESC 8` instead which is more widely supported.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ANSI escape codes are often used in UNIX and UNIX-like terminals to provide syntax highlighting.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, on compatible terminals, the following *list* command color-codes file and directory names by type.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Users can employ escape codes in their scripts by including them as part of *standard output* or *standard error*.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, the following GNU *sed* command embellishes the output of the *make* command by displaying lines containing words starting with "WARN" in reverse video and words starting with "ERR" in bright yellow on a dark red background (letter case is ignored).
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The representations of the codes are highlighted.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The following Bash function flashes the terminal (by alternately sending reverse and normal video mode codes) until the user presses a key.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It can be used to alert a programmer when a lengthy command terminates, such as with `make ; flasher` .
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The following command will reset the console, similar to the command `reset` on modern Linux systems; however it should work even on older Linux systems and on other (non-Linux) UNIX variants.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This following program creates a table of numbers from 0 to 109, each of which is displayed in the format specified by the Select Graphic Rendition escape sequence using that number as the graphic rendition code.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Pressing special keys on the keyboard, as well as outputting many xterm CSI, DCS, or OSC sequences, often produces a CSI, DCS, or OSC sequence, sent from the terminal to the computer as though the user typed it.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] When typing input on a terminal keypresses outside the normal main alphanumeric keyboard area can be sent to the host as ANSI sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For keys that have an equivalent output function, such as the cursor keys, these often mirror the output sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, for most keypresses there isn't an equivalent output sequence to use.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There are several encoding schemes, and unfortunately most terminals mix sequences from different schemes, so host software has to be able to deal with input sequences using any scheme.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] To complicate the matter, the VT terminals themselves have two schemes of input, *normal mode* and *application mode* that can be switched by the application.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is '~', the first number must be present and is a keycode number, the second number is an optional modifier value.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is a letter, the letter is the keycode value, and the optional number is the modifier value.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The modifier value defaults to 1, and after subtracting 1 is a bitmap of modifier keys being pressed: Meta+Ctrl+Alt+⇧ Shift.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `<esc>[A` to `<esc>[D` are the same as the ANSI output sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The `<modifier>` is normally omitted if no modifier keys are pressed, but most implementations always emit the `<modifier>` for F1–F4.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Xterm has a comprehensive documentation page on the various function-key and mouse input sequence schemes from DEC's VT terminals and various other terminals it emulates.
[src:chalk-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Thomas Dickey has added a lot of support to it over time; he also maintains a list of default keys used by other terminal emulators for comparison.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The **`console`** object provides access to the debugging console (e.g., the Web console in Firefox).
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Implementations of the console API may differ between runtimes.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] In particular, some console methods may work differently or not work at all in some online editors and IDEs.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To see the behavior described in this documentation, try the methods in your browser's developer tools, although even here, there are some differences between browsers.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The `console` object is available in any global scope.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Log an error message to console if the first argument is `false`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Log the number of times this line has been called with the given label.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Resets the value of the counter with the given label.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the debug log level.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Displays an interactive listing of the properties of a specified JavaScript object.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] This listing lets you use disclosure triangles to examine the contents of child objects.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Displays an XML/HTML Element representation of the specified object if possible or the JavaScript Object view if it is not possible.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the error log level.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Creates a new inline group, indenting all following output by another level.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To move back out a level, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] However, unlike `console.group()` this starts with the inline group collapsed requiring the use of a disclosure button to expand it.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the info log level.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Starts the browser's built-in profiler (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] You can specify an optional name for the profile.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] You can see the resulting profile in the browser's performance tool (for example, the Firefox performance tool).
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Starts a timer with a name specified as an input parameter.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Up to 10,000 simultaneous timers can run on a given page.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Stops the specified timer and logs the elapsed time in milliseconds since it started.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Logs the value of the specified timer to the console.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Adds a marker to the browser performance tool's timeline (Chrome or Firefox).
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a message to the console with the warning log level.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The console's most frequently used feature is logging text and other data.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] There are several categories of output you can generate using the `console.log()`, `console.info()`, `console.warn()`, `console.error()`, or `console.debug()` methods.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Each of these results in output styled differently in the log, and you can use the filtering controls provided by your browser to view only the kinds of output that interest you.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The browser will display as much information about the object as it can and wishes to.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] For example, private state of the object may be displayed too.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Certain types of objects, such as DOM elements or functions, may also be displayed in a special way.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Information about an object is lazily retrieved.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] This means that the log message shows the content of an object at the time when it's first viewed, not when it was logged.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] However, if you expand the object's details, you will see `prop: 123`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] If you are going to mutate your object and you want to prevent the logged information from being updated, you can deep-clone the object before logging it.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] There are other alternatives that work in browsers, such as `structuredClone()`, which are more effective at cloning different types of objects.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The first parameter to the logging methods can be a string containing zero or more substitution strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Each substitution string is replaced by the corresponding argument value.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "optimally useful formatting" style, for example DOM elements may be displayed the same way as they would appear in the element inspector.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Outputs a JavaScript object in the "generic JavaScript object formatting" style, usually in the form of an expandable tree.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Applies CSS style rules to all following text.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Some browsers may implement additional format specifiers.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] For example, Safari and Firefox support the C-style precision formatting `%.<precision>f`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] For example `console.log("Foo %.2f", 1.1)` will output the number to 2 decimal places: `Foo 1.10`, while `console.log("Foo %.2d", 1.1)` will output the number as two significant figures with a leading 0: `Foo 01`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Each of these pulls the next argument after the format string off the parameter list.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The text before the directive will not be affected, but the text after the directive will be styled using the CSS declarations in the parameter.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] You can use nested groups to help organize your output by visually combining related material.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To create a new nested block, call `console.group()`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The `console.groupCollapsed()` method is similar but creates the new block collapsed, requiring the use of a disclosure button to open it for reading.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To exit the current group, call `console.groupEnd()`.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] You can start a timer to calculate the duration of a specific operation.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To start one, call the `console.time()` method, giving it a name as the only parameter.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] To stop the timer, and to get the elapsed time in milliseconds, just call the `console.timeEnd()` method, again passing the timer's name as the parameter.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Up to 10,000 timers can run simultaneously on a given page.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] Notice that the timer's name is displayed both when the timer is started and when it's stopped.
[src:chalk-terminal/api-console] The console object also supports outputting a stack trace; this will show you the call path taken to reach the point at which you call `console.trace()`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chalk comes with an easy to use composable API where you just chain and nest the styles you want.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chain styles and call the last one as a method with a string argument.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Order doesn't matter, and later styles take precedent in case of a conflict.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] This simply means that `chalk.red.yellow.green` is equivalent to `chalk.green`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Multiple arguments will be separated by space.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Color support is automatically detected, but you can override it by setting the `level` property.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] You should however only do this in your own code as it applies globally to all Chalk consumers.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Detect whether the terminal supports color.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Used internally and handled for you, but exposed for convenience.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Can be overridden by the user with the flags `--color` and `--no-color`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] For situations where using `--color` is not possible, use the environment variable `FORCE_COLOR=1` (level 1), `FORCE_COLOR=2` (level 2), or `FORCE_COLOR=3` (level 3) to forcefully enable color, or `FORCE_COLOR=0` to forcefully disable.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] The use of `FORCE_COLOR` overrides all other color support checks.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Explicit 256/Truecolor mode can be enabled using the `--color=256` and `--color=16m` flags, respectively.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] `chalkStderr` contains a separate instance configured with color support detected for `stderr` stream instead of `stdout`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Override rules from `supportsColor` apply to this too.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] `supportsColorStderr` is exposed for convenience.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] All supported style strings are exposed as an array of strings for convenience.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] `colorNames` is the combination of `foregroundColorNames` and `backgroundColorNames`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chalk supports 256 colors and Truecolor (16 million colors) on supported terminal apps.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Colors are downsampled from 16 million RGB values to an ANSI color format that is supported by the terminal emulator (or by specifying `{level: n}` as a Chalk option).
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] For example, Chalk configured to run at level 1 (basic color support) will downsample an RGB value of #FF0000 (red) to 31 (ANSI escape for red).
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Background versions of these models are prefixed with `bg` and the first level of the module capitalized (e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] `hex` for foreground colors and `bgHex` for background colors).
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Since Chrome 69, ANSI escape codes are natively supported in the developer console.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] If you're on Windows, do yourself a favor and use Windows Terminal instead of `cmd.exe`.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chalk may be larger, but there is a reason for that.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] It offers a more user-friendly API, well-documented types, supports millions of colors, and covers edge cases that smaller alternatives miss.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chalk is mature, reliable, and built to last.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] But beyond the technical aspects, there's something more critical: trust and long-term maintenance.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] I have been active in open source for over a decade, and I'm committed to keeping Chalk maintained.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Smaller packages might seem appealing now, but there's no guarantee they will be around for the long term, or that they won't become malicious over time.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Chalk is also likely already in your dependency tree (since 100K+ packages depend on it), so switching won’t save space—in fact, it might increase it. npm deduplicates dependencies, so multiple Chalk instances turn into one, but adding another package alongside it will increase your overall size.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] If the goal is to clean up the ecosystem, switching away from Chalk won’t even make a dent.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] The real problem lies with packages that have very deep dependency trees (for example, those including a lot of polyfills).
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] It's better to focus on impactful changes rather than minor optimizations.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] If absolute package size is important to you, I also maintain yoctocolors, one of the smallest color packages out there.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] Micro-benchmarks are flawed because they measure performance in unrealistic, isolated scenarios, often giving a distorted view of real-world performance.
[src:chalk-terminal/chalk-chalk] All the coloring packages are more than fast enough.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The **`String`** object is used to represent and manipulate a sequence of characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Strings are useful for holding data that can be represented in text form.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Some of the most-used operations on strings are to check their `length`, to build and concatenate them using the `+` and `+=` string operators, checking for the existence or location of substrings with the `indexOf()` method, or extracting substrings with the `substring()` method.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] String primitives and string objects share many behaviors, but have other important differences and caveats.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] See "String primitives and String objects" below.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] String literals can be specified using single or double quotes, which are treated identically, or using the backtick character `.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] This last form specifies a template literal: with this form you can interpolate expressions.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] For more information on the syntax of string literals, see lexical grammar.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] There are two ways to access an individual character in a string.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] When using bracket notation for character access, attempting to delete or assign a value to these properties will not succeed.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The properties involved are neither writable nor configurable.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Note that all comparison operators, including `===` and `==`, compare strings case-sensitively.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] A common way to compare strings case-insensitively is to convert both to the same case (upper or lower) before comparing them.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The choice of whether to transform by `toUpperCase()` or `toLowerCase()` is mostly arbitrary, and neither one is fully robust when extending beyond the Latin alphabet.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] For example, the German lowercase letter `ß` and `ss` are both transformed to `SS` by `toUpperCase()`, while the Turkish letter `ı` would be falsely reported as unequal to `I` by `toLowerCase()` unless specifically using `toLocaleLowerCase("tr")`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] A locale-aware and robust solution for testing case-insensitive equality is to use the `Intl.Collator` API or the string's `localeCompare()` method — they share the same interface — with the `sensitivity` option set to `"accent"` or `"base"`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The `localeCompare()` method enables string comparison in a similar fashion as `strcmp()` — it allows sorting strings in a locale-aware manner.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Note that JavaScript distinguishes between `String` objects and primitive string values.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] String literals (denoted by double or single quotes) and strings returned from `String` calls in a non-constructor context (that is, called without using the `new` keyword) are primitive strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] In contexts where a method is to be invoked on a primitive string or a property lookup occurs, JavaScript will automatically wrap the string primitive and call the method or perform the property lookup on the wrapper object instead.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] String primitives and `String` objects also give different results when using `eval()`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Primitives passed to `eval` are treated as source code; `String` objects are treated as all other objects are, by returning the object.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] For these reasons, the code may break when it encounters `String` objects when it expects a primitive string instead, although generally, authors need not worry about the distinction.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] A `String` object can always be converted to its primitive counterpart with the `valueOf()` method.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Many built-in operations that expect strings first coerce their arguments to strings (which is largely why `String` objects behave similarly to string primitives).
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] There are several ways to achieve nearly the same effect in JavaScript.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Depending on your use case, you may want to use `${x}` (to mimic built-in behavior) or `String(x)` (to handle symbol values without throwing an error), but you should not use `"" + x`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Strings are represented fundamentally as sequences of UTF-16 code units.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] In UTF-16 encoding, every code unit is exact 16 bits long.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] This means there are a maximum of 216, or 65536 possible characters representable as single UTF-16 code units.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] This character set is called the basic multilingual plane (BMP), and includes the most common characters like the Latin, Greek, Cyrillic alphabets, as well as many East Asian characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Each code unit can be written in a string with `\u` followed by exactly four hex digits.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] However, the entire Unicode character set is much, much bigger than 65536.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The extra characters are stored in UTF-16 as *surrogate pairs*, which are pairs of 16-bit code units that represent a single character.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] To avoid ambiguity, the two parts of the pair must be between `0xD800` and `0xDFFF`, and these code units are not used to encode single-code-unit characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Each Unicode code point can be written in a string with `\u{xxxxxx}` where `xxxxxx` represents 1–6 hex digits.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Lone surrogates do not represent any Unicode character.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Strings not containing any lone surrogates are called *well-formed* strings, and are safe to be used with functions that do not deal with UTF-16 (such as `encodeURI()` or `TextEncoder`).
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] You can check if a string is well-formed with the `isWellFormed()` method, or sanitize lone surrogates with the `toWellFormed()` method.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] On top of Unicode characters, there are certain sequences of Unicode characters that should be treated as one visual unit, known as a *grapheme cluster*.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The most common case is emojis: many emojis that have a range of variations are actually formed by multiple emojis, usually joined by the <ZWJ> (`U+200D`) character.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] You must be careful which level of characters you are iterating on.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] For example, `split("")` will split by UTF-16 code units and will separate surrogate pairs.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] String indexes also refer to the index of each UTF-16 code unit.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] On the other hand, `[Symbol.iterator]()` iterates by Unicode code points.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Iterating through grapheme clusters will require some custom code.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] When called as a function, it returns primitive values of type String.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Returns a string created by using the specified sequence of Unicode values.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Returns a string created by using the specified sequence of code points.
