[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] They are of limited use, as they are based on a very old HTML standard and provide only a subset of the currently available HTML tags and attributes.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Many of them create deprecated or non-standard markup today.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] In addition, they do string concatenation without any validation or sanitation, which makes them a potential security threat when directly inserted using `innerHTML`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] Use DOM APIs such as `document.createElement()` instead.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The only escaping they do is to replace `"` in the attribute value (for `anchor()`, `fontcolor()`, `fontsize()`, and `link()`) with `&quot;`.
[src:chalk-terminal/global-objects-string] The `String()` function is a more reliable way of converting values to strings than calling the `toString()` method of the value, as the former works when used on `null` and `undefined`.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:chalk-terminal/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In computer programming, a **string** is traditionally a sequence of characters, either as a literal constant or as some kind of variable.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The latter may allow its elements to be mutated and the length changed, or it may be fixed (after creation).
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A string is often implemented as an array data structure of bytes (or words) that stores a sequence of elements, typically characters, using some character encoding.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] More general, *string* may also denote a sequence (or list) of data other than just characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Depending on the programming language and precise data type used, a variable declared to be a string may either cause storage in memory to be statically allocated for a predetermined maximum length or employ dynamic allocation to allow it to hold a variable number of elements.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] When a string appears literally in source code, it is known as a string literal or an anonymous string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In formal languages, which are used in mathematical logic and theoretical computer science, a string is a finite sequence of symbols that are chosen from a set called an alphabet.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A primary purpose of strings is to store human-readable text, like words and sentences.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Strings are used to communicate information from a computer program to the user of the program.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A program may also accept string input from its user.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Further, strings may store data expressed as characters yet not intended for human reading.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The term string may also designate a sequence of data or computer records other than characters — like a "string of bits" — but when used without qualification it refers to strings of characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean any items arranged in a line, series or succession dates back centuries.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In 19th-century typesetting, compositors used the term "string" to denote a length of type printed on paper; the string would be measured to determine the compositor's pay.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Use of the word "string" to mean "a sequence of symbols or linguistic elements in a definite order" emerged from mathematics, symbolic logic, and linguistic theory to speak about the formal behavior of symbolic systems, setting aside the symbols' meaning.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Sammet, "the first realistic string handling and pattern matching language" for computers was COMIT in the 1950s, followed by the SNOBOL language of the early 1960s.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A **string datatype** is a datatype modeled on the idea of a formal string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Strings are such an important and useful datatype that they are implemented in nearly every programming language.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In some languages they are available as primitive types and in others as composite types.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The syntax of most high-level programming languages allows for a string, usually quoted in some way, to represent an instance of a string datatype; such a meta-string is called a *literal* or *string literal*.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Although formal strings can have an arbitrary finite length, the length of strings in real languages is often constrained to an artificial maximum.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Most strings in modern programming languages are variable-length strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Of course, even variable-length strings are limited in length by the amount of available memory.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The string length can be stored as a separate integer (which may put another artificial limit on the length) or implicitly through a termination character, usually a character value with all bits zero such as in C programming language.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] These character sets were typically based on ASCII or EBCDIC.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If text in one encoding was displayed on a system using a different encoding, text was often mangled, though often somewhat readable and some computer users learned to read the mangled text.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Logographic languages such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean (known collectively as CJK) need far more than 256 characters (the limit of a one 8-bit byte per-character encoding) for reasonable representation.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The normal solutions involved keeping single-byte representations for ASCII and using two-byte representations for CJK ideographs.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Use of these with existing code led to problems with matching and cutting of strings, the severity of which depended on how the character encoding was designed.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some encodings such as the EUC family guarantee that a byte value in the ASCII range will represent only that ASCII character, making the encoding safe for systems that use those characters as field separators.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Other encodings such as ISO-2022 and Shift-JIS do not make such guarantees, making matching on byte codes unsafe.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] These encodings also were not "self-synchronizing", so that locating character boundaries required backing up to the start of a string, and pasting two strings together could result in corruption of the second string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Unicode has simplified the picture somewhat.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Most programming languages now have a datatype for Unicode strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Unicode's preferred byte stream format UTF-8 is designed not to have the problems described above for older multibyte encodings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C++, Perl and Ruby, normally allow the contents of a string to be changed after it has been created; these are termed *mutable* strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In other languages, such as Java, JavaScript, Lua, Python, and Go, the value is fixed and a new string must be created if any alteration is to be made; these are termed *immutable* strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some of these languages with immutable strings also provide another type that is mutable, such as Java and .NET's `StringBuilder`, the thread-safe Java `StringBuffer`, and the Cocoa `NSMutableString`.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Immutability brings advantages and disadvantages: while immutable strings may require inefficiently creating many copies, they are simpler and fully thread-safe.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Strings are typically implemented as arrays of bytes, characters, or code units, to allow fast access to individual units or substrings, including characters when they have a fixed length.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A few languages such as Haskell implement them as linked lists instead.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Many high-level languages provide strings as a primitive data type, such as JavaScript and PHP, while most others provide them as a composite data type, some with special language support in writing literals, for example, Java and C#.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some languages, such as C, Prolog and Erlang, avoid implementing a dedicated string datatype at all, instead adopting the convention of representing strings as lists of character codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Even in programming languages having a dedicated string type, strings can usually be iterated as a sequence of character codes, like lists of integers or other values.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Representations of strings depend heavily on the choice of character repertoire and the method of character encoding.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Older string implementations were designed to work with repertoire and encoding defined by ASCII, or more recent extensions like the ISO 8859 series.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Modern implementations often use the extensive repertoire defined by Unicode along with a variety of complex encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The term *byte string* usually indicates a general-purpose string of bytes, rather than strings of only (readable) characters, strings of bits, or such.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Byte strings often imply that bytes can take any value and any data can be stored as-is, meaning that there should be no value interpreted as a termination value.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Most string implementations are very similar to variable-length arrays with the entries storing the character codes of corresponding characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The principal difference is that, with certain encodings, a single logical character may take up more than one entry in the array.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This happens, for example, with UTF-8, where single codes (UCS code points) can take anywhere from one to four bytes, and single characters can take an arbitrary number of codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In these cases, the logical length of the string (number of characters) differs from the physical length of the array (number of bytes in use).
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] UTF-32 avoids the first part of the problem.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored in a dope vector, separate from the storage holding the actual characters.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The IBM PL/I (F) compiler used a **string dope vector** (SDV) for variable-length strings and for passing string parameters.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The SDV contains a current length and a maximum length, and is not adjacent to the string proper.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] After PL/I (F), IBM dropped the SDV in favor of length-prefixed strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The length of a string can be stored implicitly by using a special terminating character; often this is the null character (NUL), which has all bits zero, a convention used and perpetuated by the popular C programming language.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Hence, this representation is commonly referred to as a **C string**.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This representation of an *n*-character string takes *n* + 1 space (1 for the terminator), and is thus an implicit data structure.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In terminated strings, the terminating code is not an allowable character in any string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Strings with *length* field do not have this limitation and can also store arbitrary binary data.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The length of the string in the above example, "`FRANK`", is 5 characters, but it occupies 6 bytes.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Characters after the terminator do not form part of the representation; they may be either part of other data or just garbage.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Using a special byte other than null for terminating strings has historically appeared in both hardware and software, though sometimes with a value that was also a printing character.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] `$` was used by many assembler systems, `:` used by CDC systems (this character had a value of zero), and the ZX80 used `"` since this was the string delimiter in its BASIC language.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Somewhat similar, "data processing" machines like the IBM 1401 used a special word mark bit to delimit strings at the left, where the operation would start at the right.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This bit had to be clear in all other parts of the string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This meant that, while the IBM 1401 had a seven-bit word, almost no-one ever thought to use this as a feature, and override the assignment of the seventh bit to (for example) handle ASCII codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Early microcomputer software relied upon the fact that ASCII codes do not use the high-order bit, and set it to indicate the end of a string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The length of a string can also be stored explicitly, for example by prefixing the string with the length as a byte value.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This convention is used in many Pascal dialects; as a consequence, some people call such a string a **Pascal string** or **P-string**.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Storing the string length as byte limits the maximum string length to 255.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] To avoid such limitations, improved implementations of P-strings use 16-, 32-, or 64-bit words to store the string length.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] When the *length* field covers the address space, strings are limited only by the available memory.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If the length is not bounded, encoding a length *n* takes log(*n*) space (see fixed-length code), so length-prefixed strings are a succinct data structure, encoding a string of length *n* in log(*n*) + *n* space.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In the latter case, the length-prefix field itself does not have fixed length, therefore the actual string data needs to be moved when the string grows such that the length field needs to be increased.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] However, since the implementation is usually hidden, the string must be accessed and modified through member functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] `text` is a pointer to a dynamically allocated memory area, which might be expanded as needed.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Both character termination and length codes limit strings: For example, C character arrays that contain null (NUL) characters cannot be handled directly by C string library functions: Strings using a length code are limited to the maximum value of the length code.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Both of these limitations can be overcome by clever programming.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] It is possible to create data structures and functions that manipulate them that do not have the problems associated with character termination and can in principle overcome length code bounds.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] It is also possible to optimize the string represented using techniques from run length encoding (replacing repeated characters by the character value and a length) and Hamming encoding.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] While these representations are common, others are possible.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Using ropes makes certain string operations, such as insertions, deletions, and concatenations more efficient.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The differing memory layout and storage requirements of strings can affect the security of the program accessing the string data.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] String representations requiring a terminating character are commonly susceptible to buffer overflow problems if the terminating character is not present, caused by a coding error or an attacker deliberately altering the data.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] String representations adopting a separate length field are also susceptible if the length can be manipulated.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In such cases, program code accessing the string data requires bounds checking to ensure that it does not inadvertently access or change data outside of the string memory limits.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] String data is frequently obtained from user input to a program.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] As such, it is the responsibility of the program to validate the string to ensure that it represents the expected format.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Performing limited or no validation of user input can cause a program to be vulnerable to code injection attacks.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Sometimes, strings need to be embedded inside a text file that is both human-readable and intended for consumption by a machine.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This is needed in, for example, source code of programming languages, or in configuration files.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In this case, the NUL character does not work well as a terminator since it is normally invisible (non-printable) and is difficult to input via a keyboard.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Storing the string length would also be inconvenient as manual computation and tracking of the length is tedious and error-prone.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] While character strings are very common uses of strings, a string in computer science may refer generically to any sequence of homogeneously typed data.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A bit string or byte string, for example, may be used to represent non-textual binary data retrieved from a communications medium.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This data may or may not be represented by a string-specific datatype, depending on the needs of the application, the desire of the programmer, and the capabilities of the programming language being used.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If the programming language's string implementation is not 8-bit clean, data corruption may ensue.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] C programmers draw a sharp distinction between a "string", aka a "string of characters", which by definition is always null terminated, vs. an "array of characters" which may be stored in the same array but is often not null terminated.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Using C string handling functions on such an array of characters often seems to work, but later leads to security problems.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] There are many algorithms for processing strings, each with various trade-offs.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Competing algorithms can be analyzed with respect to run time, storage requirements, and so forth.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The name **stringology** was coined in 1984 by computer scientist Zvi Galil for the theory of algorithms and data structures used for string processing.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Advanced string algorithms often employ complex mechanisms and data structures, among them suffix trees and finite-state machines.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Character strings are such a useful datatype that several languages have been designed in order to make string processing applications easy to write.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Many Unix utilities perform simple string manipulations and can be used to easily program some powerful string processing algorithms.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Files and finite streams may be viewed as strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some APIs like Multimedia Control Interface, embedded SQL or printf use strings to hold commands that will be interpreted.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Many scripting programming languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, and Tcl employ regular expressions to facilitate text operations.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Perl is particularly noted for its regular expression use, and many other languages and applications implement Perl compatible regular expressions.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some languages such as Perl and Ruby support string interpolation, which permits arbitrary expressions to be evaluated and included in string literals.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] String functions are used to create strings or change the contents of a mutable string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] They also are used to query information about a string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The set of functions and their names varies depending on the computer programming language.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The most basic example of a string function is the string length function – the function that returns the length of a string (not counting any terminator characters or any of the string's internal structural information) and does not modify the string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This function is often named `length`, `len`, or `size`.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] For example, `length("hello world")` would return 11.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Another common function is concatenation, where a new string is created by appending two strings, often this is the + addition operator.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Some microprocessor's instruction set architectures contain direct support for string operations, such as block copy (e.g.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Let $\Sigma$ be a finite set of distinct, unambiguous symbols (alternatively called characters), called the alphabet.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A **string** (or **word** or **expression**) over $\Sigma$ is any finite sequence of symbols from $\Sigma$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The *length* of a string s is the number of symbols in s (the length of the sequence) and can be any non-negative integer; it is often denoted as $|s|$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The *empty string* is the unique string over $\Sigma$ of length 0 , and is denoted $\varepsilon$ or $\lambda$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of length n is denoted $\Sigma ^{n}$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] We have $\Sigma ^{0}=\{\varepsilon \}$ for every alphabet $\Sigma$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The set of all strings over $\Sigma$ of any length is the Kleene closure of $\Sigma$ and is denoted $\Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Although the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ itself is countably infinite, each element of $\Sigma ^{*}$ is a string of finite length.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A set of strings over $\Sigma$ (i.e. any subset of $\Sigma ^{*}$ ) is called a *formal language* over $\Sigma$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] String concatenation is an associative, but non-commutative operation.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The empty string $\varepsilon$ serves as the identity element; for any string s , $\varepsilon s=s\varepsilon =s$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Therefore, the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ and the concatenation operation form a monoid, the free monoid generated by $\Sigma$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] In addition, the length function defines a monoid homomorphism from $\Sigma ^{*}$ to the non-negative integers (that is, a function $L:\Sigma ^{*}\mapsto \mathbb {N} \cup \{0\}$ , such that $L(st)=L(s)+L(t)\quad \forall s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ ).
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a *substring* or *factor* of t if there exist (possibly empty) strings u and v such that $t=usv$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The relation "is a substring of" defines a partial order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the least element of which is the empty string.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A string s is said to be a prefix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=su$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* prefix of t .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Symmetrically, a string s is said to be a suffix of t if there exists a string u such that $t=us$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If u is nonempty, s is said to be a *proper* suffix of t .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Suffixes and prefixes are substrings of t .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Both the relations "is a prefix of" and "is a suffix of" are prefix orders.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The reverse of a string is a string with the same symbols but in reverse order.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] For example, if $s={\texttt {abc}}$ (where ${\texttt {a}}$ , ${\texttt {b}}$ , and ${\texttt {c}}$ are symbols of the alphabet), then the reverse of s is ${\texttt {cba}}$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A string that is the reverse of itself (e.g., $s={\texttt {madam}}$ ) is called a palindrome, which also includes the empty string and all strings of length 1 .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A string $s=uv$ is said to be a rotation of t if $t=vu$ .
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] It is often useful to define an ordering on a set of strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] If the alphabet $\Sigma$ has a total order (cf. alphabetical order) one can define a total order on $\Sigma ^{*}$ called lexicographical order.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The lexicographical order is total if the alphabetical order is, but is not well-founded for any nontrivial alphabet, even if the alphabetical order is.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] See Shortlex for an alternative string ordering that preserves well-foundedness.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] A number of additional operations on strings commonly occur in the formal theory.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] These are given in the article on string operations.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] The natural topology on the set of fixed-length strings or variable-length strings is the discrete topology, but the natural topology on the set of infinite strings is the limit topology, viewing the set of infinite strings as the inverse limit of the sets of finite strings.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] This is the construction used for the *p*-adic numbers and some constructions of the Cantor set, and yields the same topology.
[src:chalk-terminal/string-computer-science] Isomorphisms between string representations of topologies can be found by normalizing according to the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:chalk-terminal/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
